  "fullDescription": "Mummification was the quintessential Egyptian funerary practice, developed over millennia to preserve the body (khat) for the soul's (ba and ka) eventual reunion in the afterlife. Based on the mythical precedent of Osiris‚Äîmurdered, dismembered by Set, and reassembled by Isis and Anubis to become lord of the dead‚Äîthe process involved removing internal organs, desiccating the body with natron salt, treating it with oils and resins, and wrapping it in hundreds of meters of linen. The ritual took approximately 70 days and was performed by specialized priests wearing Anubis masks, with specific prayers and spells recited at each stage. Vital organs (lungs, stomach, intestines, liver) were individually preserved in canopic jars protected by the Four Sons of Horus. The heart was left in the body as the seat of intelligence and morality, needed for the Weighing of the Heart judgment before Osiris. Protective amulets‚Äîscarabs, djed pillars, wadjet eyes‚Äîwere placed throughout the wrappings, and the completed mummy was adorned with a mask (golden for royalty) depicting the idealized deceased as Osiris. The entire process was not merely physical preservation but spiritual transformation, turning the deceased into an akh (effective spirit) capable of eternal existence.",
