  "effects": "Successful mummification ensured the preservation of the physical body necessary for the ba and ka to recognize and reunite with it in the afterlife. The process transformed the deceased into an akh (effective spirit) capable of dwelling eternally in the Field of Reeds. Protective amulets and spells defended against dangers in the Duat. The ritual literally made the deceased into an Osiris (osiris N), granting them the god's regenerative power and rulership over their own afterlife domain. For the living, proper mummification fulfilled sacred duty to the deceased and maintained ma'at (cosmic order).",

  "warnings": "Improper mummification could doom the deceased to non-existence. The preservation had to be done correctly or the ba and ka would not recognize the body. Tomb robbers who violated mummies risked terrible curses and divine retribution. The process was extremely expensive‚Äîelaborate royal mummification cost fortunes, while the poor received only basic preservation or simple desert burial. Missing organs (especially the heart) or damaged bodies complicated afterlife existence.",

