      "culturalSignificance": "Practiced from approximately 3500 BCE to 500 CE (over 4,000 years), mummification shaped Egyptian civilization profoundly. It drove developments in medicine, chemistry, and preservation technology. The funerary industry employed vast numbers and consumed enormous resources. Royal mummification was state ritual confirming pharaonic divinity. The practice spread to pets and sacred animals. Modern Egyptology began partly through study of mummies, and they remain powerful symbols of ancient Egypt."
